  "chunk_index": 16,
  "summary": "The Earl of Carrington enters his study to find George Roxburgh, Major McRoss, and a muscular, noble-looking man. Inspector Bartle arrives to investigate the death of \"Count Stanislaus,\" whom Roxburgh reveals is actually Prince Michael of Hesse. The Prince had visited the villa to discuss loan terms with Herman Eschelbacher; specifically, the Prince had promised oil concessions to Isakov's company in exchange for support of his ascension to the throne, a move favored by the British government.\n\nInspector Bartle outlines the facts of the case: the Prince was shot with a revolver at approximately 11:45 p.m., a time indicated by his broken watch. No gunshot was heard, and the weapon is missing. The Earl notes that the house contained the Prince, his servant Boris Anschutz, Eschelbacher, an employee named Everly, and an American collector named Hiram Fisk.\n\nBartle reveals that footprints found near the victim's window match muddy boots belonging to a young man named Anthony Kidd, who checked into the Happy Cricketer Inn at midnight. While Roxburgh calls for Kidd's arrest, Bartle finds it suspicious that Kidd has remained at the inn rather than fleeing. During this discussion, a man calling himself Anthony Kade arrives, claiming to have urgent information regarding the tragedy. The name \"Anthony Kade\" causes visible surprise among the four men in the room as Kade enters, claiming he has come to investigate the rumors of murder.",
